## Run the full Gate C.1 suite

This iterates every fixture and prints a digest. Pause between rounds — the
reviewer's job is to walk through each one and rate the output, then suggest prompt
edits. Re-run after each prompt iteration.

```elixir
for fixture <- fixtures do
  IO.puts("\n=========================================")
  IO.puts("=== #{fixture.label}")
  IO.puts("=========================================\n")
  IO.puts(fixture.text)
  IO.puts("\n--- DraftCards ---\n")

  case Manillum.Archive.extract_drafts(fixture.text) do
    {:ok, drafts} ->
      IO.puts("count: #{length(drafts)}")

      drafts
      |> Enum.with_index(1)
      |> Enum.each(fn {%Manillum.Archive.Cataloging.DraftCard{} = d, i} ->
        IO.puts(
          "  #{i}. #{d.drawer} · #{d.date_token} · #{d.slug} (#{d.card_type})"
        )

        IO.puts("     front: #{d.front}")
        IO.puts("     back : #{d.back}")
        IO.puts("     tags : #{inspect(d.tags)}")
      end)

    {:error, error} ->
      IO.inspect(error, label: "ERROR", limit: :infinity, printable_limit: :infinity)
  end
end

:ok
```

## Reviewer checklist (per spec §5 Stream C, Gate C.1)

For each fixture above, ask:

* **Card count** — is the number of atomic facts produced appropriate to the source?
  Too few = the LLM is bundling distinct facts. Too many = it's splitting a single
  fact into pieces.
* **Slugs sensible** — do they read as content-relevant tokens? Numeric / letter
  suffixes (`-2`, `-A`) are a smell (§7.4 style guide).
* **Dates correct** — does `date_token` match what the text actually says?
  Hallucinated years are a critical failure mode.
* **Tags reasonable** — would these tags help group the card in the Reference view?
  1–4 is the target range.
* **Entities identified** — does the `entities` list catch named people, places, sources
  in the back text? Generic nouns should be omitted.
* **Front / back atomic** — does each card stand alone? Could a reviewer see the
  card without the conversation context and still understand it?

When all 10 fixtures consistently produce good cards, sign off Gate C.1 in the
project index and proceed to Gate C.2 (end-to-end async pipeline).

## Gate C.2 — End-to-end Capture → Card flow

Gate C.2 is the slice's end-to-end pipeline gate (per spec §5 Stream C and the
Gate C.2 review packet on the project index). The cells below mirror the IEx
verification recipe in the runbook — they exercise:

1. `Manillum.Archive.submit/1` creates a `:pending` capture.
2. The AshOban scan trigger (`where expr(status == :pending)`) picks it up
   when drained synchronously via `AshOban.Test.schedule_and_run_triggers/1`.
3. `RunCataloging` flips status `:pending → :cataloging → :catalogued`,
   issues an LLM call, and persists draft Cards with `:draft` status +
   `capture_id` set.
4. PubSub `:cards_drafted` fires on `"user:#{user_id}:cataloging"`.

> **This hits a real Anthropic call (~$0.001 per run).** No stub here — the
> Mix standalone runtime boots the full app supervisor (Oban + PubSub
> included), so the trigger pipeline runs against the dev DB and a live LLM.

### 1. Seed a user, subscribe to the cataloging topic

A fresh email per run avoids tripping the `user_email` identity if the
notebook is re-run against the same dev DB. Subscribing on `self()` gives
the next cell's `receive` access to the broadcast.

```elixir
email = "gate-c2-#{System.system_time(:millisecond)}@example.com"
user = Ash.Seed.seed!(Manillum.Accounts.User, %{email: email})

topic = "user:#{user.id}:cataloging"
Phoenix.PubSub.subscribe(Manillum.PubSub, topic)

%{user_id: user.id, email: email, topic: topic}
```

### 2. Submit a capture (what LiveView `+ FILE` will call)

The §5 Stream C interface line in the spec writes this as
`Manillum.Archive.create!(:submit, %{...})`; the equivalent code-interface
call exposed on the `Manillum.Archive` domain is `submit/1`.

```elixir
{:ok, capture} =
  Manillum.Archive.submit(%{
    user_id: user.id,
    source_text: """
    Between roughly 1200 and 1150 BCE, the Bronze Age palace economies of
    the eastern Mediterranean — Mycenaean Greece, Hittite Anatolia, and
    Ugarit on the Syrian coast — collapsed in close succession. The
    current consensus blames a "systems collapse" rather than a single
    cause.
    """,
    scope: :whole,
    conversation_id: Ash.UUID.generate()
  })

%{id: capture.id, status: capture.status, scope: capture.scope}
```

### 3. Drive the AshOban scan trigger synchronously

`AshOban.Test.schedule_and_run_triggers/1` schedules the trigger jobs for
`Manillum.Archive.Capture` and drains the `:cataloging` queue inline,
returning the Oban drain result. In production the cron tick fires every
minute; here we drain it on demand.

```elixir
result = AshOban.Test.schedule_and_run_triggers(Manillum.Archive.Capture)
```

### 4. Reload — confirm `:pending → :cataloging → :catalogued`

The intermediate `:cataloging` write happens inside `RunCataloging`'s
`before_action`; by the time the trigger drains, the row is at
`:catalogued` (or `:failed`). `error_reason` should be `nil` on the
happy path.

```elixir
reloaded = Ash.get!(Manillum.Archive.Capture, capture.id, authorize?: false)

%{
  status: reloaded.status,
  error_reason: reloaded.error_reason,
  updated_at: reloaded.updated_at
}
```

### 5. List the draft Cards persisted with `capture_id` set

```elixir
require Ash.Query

cards =
  Manillum.Archive.Card
  |> Ash.Query.filter(capture_id == ^capture.id)
  |> Ash.read!(authorize?: false)

cards
|> Enum.map(fn card ->
  %{
    status: card.status,
    capture_id: card.capture_id,
    call_number: "#{card.drawer} · #{card.date_token} · #{card.slug}",
    front: card.front
  }
end)
```

### 6. Receive the `:cards_drafted` broadcast

`schedule_and_run_triggers/1` is synchronous, so the broadcast has
already fired by the time we get here. A short timeout covers any tiny
PubSub delivery latency.

```elixir
receive do
  {:cards_drafted, payload} ->
    IO.puts("✓ :cards_drafted received")
    IO.inspect(payload, label: "payload")
    {:received, payload}

  {:cards_drafting_failed, payload} ->
    IO.puts("✗ :cards_drafting_failed — pipeline error path was hit")
    IO.inspect(payload, label: "failure")
    {:failed, payload}
after
  500 ->
    IO.puts("✗ no broadcast within 500ms — pipeline did not reach the broadcast step")
    :timeout
end
```

### 7. Gate C.2 sign-off checklist

For each cell above, confirm:

- **§ 2** — `submit/1` returned `{:ok, %Capture{status: :pending}}`.
- **§ 3** — `schedule_and_run_triggers/1` reported `success: 1` (or more)
  with no failures / discards.
- **§ 4** — the reloaded capture's `status` is `:catalogued` and
  `error_reason` is `nil` (happy path) — or `:catalogued` with a
  `"collisions or create errors"` note if any per-draft skips fired.
- **§ 5** — at least one persisted Card with `status: :draft` and
  `capture_id` matching the submitted capture.
- **§ 6** — `{:cards_drafted, payload}` arrived with the expected
  `capture_id`, `conversation_id`, and a non-empty `draft_ids` list.

When all five pass, sign off Gate C.2 on the project index and merge
the slice. The slug-collision skip path and `:cards_drafting_failed`
broadcast are already exercised by the test suite
(`test/manillum/archive/capture_test.exs`); re-running them here is
optional — pre-seed a colliding `Card` (same `user_id / drawer /
date_token / slug` as the LLM will produce) and observe `error_reason`
populate while no new draft persists.
